@jackylk  everything looks great.
One comment:Can you list what are the exact benefits for this feature?  main purpose is for saving as to different folder , not CarbonData's default folder ?

As per my understanding:
before : the database name is using the default, users are not aware of it, users don't need to input database as parameter.

So i feel that both solution just need to input table name.

Since CarbonData is a file format, so ideally it should support saving it to any folder. Currently we are forcing database and table folder structure, it makes the usage different from other Spark file datasource like parquet and orc. 
And I think by accepting only path parameter, it is easier to integrate with Spark 2.0 and other processing framework

There are few object creations, arraycopies and equalIgnorecase are added for each row/field. It might impact actual loading performance irrespective of badrecordlogger is enabled or not.  Please try to avoid these operations.

@jackylk I have one doubt at a time number of records to sort is very less suppose 1 million and in that case we can sort data in memory , but what about scenario like when multiple table is getting loaded at the same time in that case memory consumption will be two high if all the tables are keeping all the data  in memory  and java Arrays sorting is out-of-place sorting so at a time for suppose 1 millions records per table then 10 tables data will be 10 million and as out-of-sorting will make it 20 million so in that case it may go out of memory or it may cause to much gc
@Zhangshunyu I think we can keep total number of blocklet of a block in Btree itself and we need only valid blocklet number scanned blocklet number is not required
